fields.title: Who am I?
fields.content:
I'm Nathalia, a 26-year-old living in Limerick, Ireland. Although I was born in Brazil, I now call this beautiful city my home. Alongside my various other jobs, I'm an aspiring artist and a dedicated mom who is eager to sell her art so she can stay home with her baby.

Throughout my life, I've always felt a sense of hesitation when it comes to showcasing my art or putting myself out there. However, love has changed everything for me. The most important thing now is having the opportunity to raise my baby by my side, which is why I've made the decision to start this business.

Drawing has been a passion of mine since childhood, and I've always loved creating personalized cards for my loved ones. In Ireland, I've noticed the profound appreciation for giving cards, with dedicated stores just for that purpose!

I'll be crafting heartfelt cards that express love, gratitude, and care for your loved ones. These meaningful and personalized gifts are perfect for the people who matter the most to you.

Hope you like it ✨️😃

fields.title: This card means a lot to me (and to my husband)! ✨️
fields.content:
My husband works in shifts, and some nights I have to sleep alone. During my pregnancy, I missed him dearly and noticed how tired he was. That's when I decided to create something inspiring for him. I drew our family and left a heartfelt note on the other side of the paper, reminding him that no matter what, we are in this together!

It may be simple, but its significance is profound. I drew our beloved plant, our fish, and our baby (who was still in my belly at the time). 🐟🌿👶🏻

Every day, we look at this card and are reminded of the love we share ✨️💕

fields.title: A Drawing Story
fields.content:
This is the first post in the "A Drawing Story" series! 🌟

As an amateur and beginner, it's very challenging for me to create a #drawing that's 100% original without looking at any references. Now, I'm trying to exercise my #creativity more to create increasingly authentic drawings. I'm searching for my own style! Every day, I will put more of my soul and identity into my creations.

🌻 Where am I starting? 🌻

1. Inspiration - I think of something I would like to draw. It could be by trying to imagine something or browsing @Pinterest until I find something that interests me.

2. Purpose - This time, I wanted to create a drawing for my husband's aunt, who supported us a lot during the pregnancy and sent gifts for our baby.

3. Meaning - If I could, I would have sent her #flowers, so I decided to do that through my drawing. I love her energy and find her very uplifting, so when I saw some #sunflowers, I became very interested. I saw an image from #StudioGhibli with #clouds, so I also decided to create clouds behind the flowers. I enjoy drawing leaves, so I decided to add a branch without flowers, just to make it more like me. I saw one of the drawings that had a small moon and I decided to make a large moon in my drawing.

4. Small details - I usually don't like the drawing when I start. I spend a lot of time looking at it and trying to figure out what seems off. In this drawing, I spent a lot of time on the clouds because they were too round, and I wanted a more realistic drawing. So, I tried blending and mixing more colors, and it got closer to what I wanted. The sunflowers weren't standing out, and after observing them for a while, I realized that the petals were too small, so I decided to make them bigger.

I hope these tips help other #beginners. These are the steps I try to follow to stimulate my creativity. Additionally, I aim to create drawings with significant meaning, and that makes all the difference. I always make them for someone, and I hope that one day I can make one for myself with the same enthusiasm. 💛

fields.title: Journey Through My Graphic Design Course
fields.content:
I'm finally able to continue my studies after pregnancy and post-partum. Today I delivered one assignment from my Graphic Design course. 

I was supposed to take a raw photo, resize it for use in web projects and use Photoshop's crop tool to crop it taking into consideration the rule of thirds.

In the picture, my model, Thomas Zakczewiski.

fields.title: Art Project between Ireland and Brazil
fields.content:
Last week I received this lovely book from the Irish Embassy in Brazil. The book marks the centenary of the the James Joyce's masterpiece, Ulysses. Throughout the last year we worked very hard to launch the project hashtag#Ulysses100PelosOlhosBrasileiros, which we selected 18 students from 18 public universities in Brazil to depict a mural about each chapter of the book.

I'm very proud that I could be part of it. The project was huge success!

Many thanks to Ambassador Sean Hoy who trusted me with this special project. Now I'll continue my journey in Ireland, with lots of great opportunities and important works to be done.

fields.title: Art for Change: Empowering Voices, Inspiring Action
fields.content:
Art has always been a potent force for driving social change and amplifying the voices of the marginalized. From the revolutionary brushstrokes of political artists to the poignant verses of socially conscious poets, art has served as a powerful medium for challenging the status quo and inspiring meaningful action. Through its emotive power and universal appeal, art transcends boundaries, sparking dialogue, fostering empathy, and galvanizing communities to confront pressing social issues head-on.

At its core, art for change is about giving voice to the voiceless and shedding light on the injustices that plague our society. Artists, activists, and cultural influencers have long recognized the transformative potential of art as a tool for advocacy and activism. Whether through visual art, music, theater, or literature, artists harness the power of creativity to provoke thought, evoke emotion, and drive positive social change. By shining a spotlight on issues such as racial inequality, gender discrimination, environmental degradation, and political corruption, art empowers individuals to confront uncomfortable truths and envision a more just and equitable world.

In an era marked by unprecedented global challenges, the role of art in effecting change has never been more critical. As we navigate complex social, political, and environmental issues, art provides a beacon of hope, resilience, and resistance. By embracing art as a catalyst for social transformation, we can harness its transformative power to build bridges, bridge divides, and create a more inclusive and compassionate society for all. Through collective action and creative expression, we can harness the power of art to inspire lasting change and shape a better future for generations to come.
